SENATE RESOLUTION 296
By Massey
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Diane Jordan of Knox
County.
WHEREAS, we were greatly saddened to learn of the passing of Diane Jordan of Knox
County; and
WHEREAS, Mrs. Jordan was a trailblazing figure in local politics and devoted public
servant who worked assiduously to improve the quality of life for her fellow citizens in numerous
capacities; and
WHEREAS, Diane Jordan was the first Black woman to serve on the Knox County
Commission; her tenure spanned from 1994 to 2007, during which time she was a Democrat
representing District 6; and
WHEREAS, Mrs. Jordan first ran for office with the intention of shining a light on police
brutality, which she said permeated her predominantly Black district; during her second term as
a Knox County commissioner, she shifted her focus to economic development; and
WHEREAS, after her political career came to a close, she continued to serve her
community in various capacities, including as a member of the Beck Cultural Center's Board of
Directors, Drug Free America, and the Knoxville NAACP; she also served on the Knox County
Election Commission; and
WHEREAS, a graduate of Austin-East Magnet High School, Mrs. Jordan worked in
reservations for Delta Airlines for twenty years; she obtained her real estate license in the 1990s
and was one of the few women in Knox County to hold an auctioneer's license; and
WHEREAS, Mrs. Jordan was often duly lauded for the positive impact she had on Knox
County; she was the recipient of the YWCA's 1990 Tribute to Women Award for volunteer
SR0296
013364
- 1 -

service, and in 2017, the Interstate 275 bridge over Elm Street/Bernard Avenue was renamed
"Diane Jordan Pass" in her honor; and
WHEREAS, in addition to her important work throughout the community, Mrs. Jordan
was known for her extensive hat collection that included more than 125 cowboy hats and over
250 Sunday hats, which she donned as First Lady of her church; and
WHEREAS, a beloved family matriarch, Diane Jordan is survived by her husband of
forty-one years, Reverend John Jordan; eight children; and more than twenty grandchildren;
and
WHEREAS, Mrs. Jordan's life stands as a powerful testament to service, excellence,
and perseverance; her legacy is woven into the fabric of her community and will endure for
generations to come; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that we should pause to remember the bountiful life of this
exceptional individual and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, that we honor the memory of Diane
Jordan, reflecting fondly upon her impeccable character and her stalwart commitment to living
the examined life with courage and conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we express our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Mrs. Jordan.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy.
